9.2. Exceptions to Confidentiality Obligation. The obligation of confidentiality set forth in Section 9.1 shall be subject to exceptions, as follows:

(a) If a Governmental Authority or court of competent jurisdiction mandates disclosure through an order or regulation, the Recipient is relieved from the confidentiality obligation, provided that the Recipient shall endeavor to notify the other Party in advance and give them a reasonable opportunity to challenge the disclosure requirement. However, if a protective order or injunctive relief is granted, the Recipient shall abide by its terms.

(b) The Recipient may also disclose information when it can be proven that:
   (i) the information was publicly available prior to the disclosure and not as a result of any breach of this Agreement by the Recipient, its directors, officers, employees or agents;
   (ii) the Recipient had knowledge of the information before the date of disclosure, except for cases where such knowledge was obtained through disclosure by the other Party under another agreement;
   (iii) the information was received from an independent third party who is not under a duty of confidentiality to either Party.
